; // return True, The event can be booked. \nmyCalendarTwo.book(10, 40); // return True, The event can be double booked. \nmyCalendarTwo.book(5, 15);  // return False, The event cannot be booked, because it would result in a triple booking.\nmyCalendarTwo.book(5, 10); // return True, The event can be booked, as it does not use time 10 which is already double booked.\nmyCalendarTwo.book(25, 55); // return True, The event can be booked, as the time in [25, 40) will be double booked with the third event, the time [40, 50) will be single booked, and the time [50, 55) will be double booked with the second event.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `0 <= start < end <= 10⁹`\n\n- At most `1000` calls will be made to `book`.","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Array","Binary Search","Design","Segment Tree","Prefix Sum","Ordered Set"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Medium","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"You are implementing a program to use as your calendar. We can add a new event if adding the event will not cause a **triple booking**.\n\nA **triple booking** happens when three events have some non-empty intersection (i.e., some moment is common to all the three events.).\n\nThe event can be represented as a pair of integers `startTime` and `endTime` that represents a booking on the half-open interval `[startTime, endTime)`, the range of real numbers `x` such that `startTime <= x < endTime`.\n\nImplement the `MyCalendarTwo` class:\n\n- `MyCalendarTwo()` Initializes the calendar object.\n\n- `boolean book(int startTime, int endTime)` Returns `true` if the event can be added to the calendar successfully without causing a **triple booking**. Otherwise, return `false` and do not add the event to the calendar.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput\n[\"MyCalendarTwo\", \"book\", \"book\", \"book\", \"book\", \"book\", \"book\"]\n[[], [10, 20], [50, 60], [10, 40], [5, 15], [5, 10], [25, 55]]\nOutput\n[null, true, true, t