t.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"alt":"Problem image","contentType":"image/jpeg","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/0750-number-of-corner-rectangles/750-cornerrec1-grid.jpg","sequence":1,"sha256":"2f8ae70006fd0f1cc719b3e4b8c601d541b4ae36cc7abbdfae7723e123fda364","type":"image"},{"sequence":2,"text":"Input: grid = [[1,0,0,1,0],[0,0,1,0,1],[0,0,0,1,0],[1,0,1,0,1]]\nOutput: 1\nExplanation: There is only one corner rectangle, with corners grid[1][2], grid[1][4], grid[3][2], grid[3][4].","type":"code"},{"sequence":3,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"alt":"Problem image","contentType":"image/jpeg","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/0750-number-of-corner-rectangles/750-cornerrec2-grid.jpg","sequence":4,"sha256":"42de43628ec858611a80272412c0b0e5b39024056390a815a7116ac8b1a03bd3","type":"image"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: grid = [[1,1,1],[1,1,1],[1,1,1]]\nOutput: 9\nExplanation: There are four 2x2 rectangles, four 2x3 and 3x2 rectangles, and one 3x3 rectangle.","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Example 3:**","type":"text"},{"alt":"Problem image","contentType":"image/jpeg","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/0750-number-of-corner-rectangles/750-cornerrec3-grid.jpg","sequence":7,"sha256":"408ebb164a0bfa16621c00f3372408c19bd25d0bafac321f87df215044bd424a","type":"image"},{"sequence":8,"text":"Input: grid = [[1,1,1,1]]\nOutput: 0\nExplanation: Rectangles must have four distinct corners.","type":"code"},{"sequence":9,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `m == grid.length`\n\n- `n == grid[i].length`\n\n- `1 <= m, n <= 200`\n\n- `grid[i][j]` is either `0` or `1`.\n\n- The number of `1`'s in the grid is in the range `[1, 6000]`.","type":"text"}],"difficulty":"Medium","examples":[],"paidOnly":false,"problem":"Given an `m x n` integer matrix `grid` where each entry is only `0` or `1`, return *the number of **corner rectangles***.\n\nA **corner rectangle** is four distinct `1`'s on the grid that forms an axis-aligned rectangle. Note that only the corners need to have the value `1`. Also, all four `1`'s used must be distinct.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/0750-number-of-corner-rectangles/750-cornerrec1-grid.jpg]]\n\nInput: grid = [[1,0,0,1,0],[0,0,1,0,1],[0,0,0,1,0],[1,0,1,0,1]]\nOutput: 1\nExplanation: There is only one corner rectangle, with corners grid[1][2], grid[1][4], grid[3][2], grid[3][4].\n\n**Example 2:**\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/0750-number-of-corner-rectangles/750-cornerrec2-grid.jpg]]\n\nInput: grid = [[1,1,1],[1,1,1],[1,1,1]]\nOutput: 9\nExplanation: There are four 2x2 rectangles, four 2x3 and 3x2 rectangles, and one 3x3 rectangle.\n\n**Example 3:**\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/0750-number-of-corner-rectangles/750-cornerrec3-grid.jpg]]\n\nInput: grid = [[1,1,1,1]]\nOutput: 0\nExplanation: Rectangles must have four distinct corners.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `m == grid.length`\n\n- `n == grid[i].length`\n\n- `1 <= m, n <= 200`\n\n- `grid[i][j]` is either `0` or `1`.\n\n- The number of `1`'s in the grid is in the range `[1, 6000]`.","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/number-of-corner-rectangles/","problemName":"Number Of Corner Rectangles","problemNumber":750,"problemSlug":"number-of-corner-rectangles","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":750,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["Bit Manipulation","String"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"An **IP address** is a formatted 32-bit unsigned integer where each group of 8 bits is printed as a decimal number and the dot character `'.'` splits the groups.\n\n- For example, the binary number `00001111 10001000 11111111 01101011` (spaces added for clarity) formatted as an IP address would be `\"15.136.255.107\"`.\n\nA **CIDR block** is a format used to denote a specific set of IP addresses. It is a string consisting of a base IP address, followed by a slash, followed by a prefix length `k`. The addresses it covers are all the IPs whose **first `k` bits** are the same as the base IP address.\n\n- For example, `\"123.45.67.89/20\"` is a CIDR block with a prefix length of `20`. Any IP address whose binary representation matches `01111011 00101101 0100xxxx xxxxxxxx`, where `x` can be either `0` or `1`, is in the set covered by the CIDR block.\n\nYou are given a start IP address `ip` and the number of IP addresses we need to cover `n`. Your goal is to use **as few CIDR blocks as possible** to cover all the IP addresses in the **inclusive** range `[ip, ip + n - 1]` **exactly**. No other IP addresses outside of the range should be covered.\n\nReturn *the **shortest** list of **CIDR blocks** that covers the range of IP addresses. If there are multiple answers, return **any** of them*.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: ip = \"255.0.0.7\", n = 10\nOutput: [\"255.0.0.7/32\",\"255.0.0.8/29\",\"255.0.0.16/32\"]\nExplanation:\nThe IP addresses that need to be covered are:\n- 255.0.0.7  -> 11111111 00000000 00000000 00000111\n- 255.0.0.8  -> 11111111 00000000 00000000 00001000\n- 255.0.0.9  -> 11111111 00000000 00000000 00001001\n- 255.0.0.10 -> 11111111 00000000 00000000 00001010\n- 255.0.0.11 -> 11111111 00000000 00000000 00001011\n- 255.0.0.12 -> 11111111 00000000 00000000 00001100\n- 255.0.0.13 -> 11111111 00000000 00000000 00001101\n- 255.0.0.14 -> 11111111 00000000 00000000 00001110\n- 255.0.0.15 -> 11111111 00000000 00000000 00001111\n- 255.0.0.16 -> 11111111 00000000 00000000 00010000\nThe CIDR block \"255.0.0.7/32\" covers the first address.\nThe CIDR block \"255.0.0.8/29\" covers the middle 8 addresses (binary format of 11111111 00000000 00000000 00001xxx).\nThe CIDR block \"255.0.0.16/32\" covers the last address.\nNote that while the CIDR block \"255.0.0.0/28\" does cover all the addresses, it also includes addresses outside of the range, so we cannot use it.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: ip = \"117.145.102.62\", n = 8\nOutput: [\