ll, it stays in place.\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/0755-pour-water/755-pour12-grid.jpg]]\n\nThe next droplet falls at index k = 3. Since the new droplet moving left will eventually make it fall, it moves left. Notice that the droplet still preferred to move left, even though it could move right (and moving right makes it fall quicker.)\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/0755-pour-water/755-pour13-grid.jpg]]\n\nThe third droplet falls at index k = 3. Since moving left would not eventually make it fall, it tries to move right. Since moving right would eventually make it fall, it moves right.\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/0755-pour-water/755-pour14-grid.jpg]]\n\nFinally, the fourth droplet falls at index k = 3. Since moving left would not eventually make it fall, it tries to move right. Since moving right would not eventually make it fall, it stays in place.\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/0755-pour-water/755-pour15-grid.jpg]]\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: heights = [1,2,3,4], volume = 2, k = 2\nOutput: [2,3,3,4]\nExplanation: The last droplet settles at index 1, since moving further left would not cause it to eventually fall to a lower height.\n\n**Example 3:**\n\nInput: heights = [3,1,3], volume = 5, k = 1\nOutput: [4,4,4]\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= heights.length <= 100`\n\n- `0 <= heights[i] <= 99`\n\n- `0 <= volume <= 2000`\n\n- `0 <= k < heights.length`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/pour-water/","problemName":"Pour Water","problemNumber":755,"problemSlug":"pour-water","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":755,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[{"assetIndex":0,"bytes":22597,"contentType":"image/jpeg","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/0756-pyramid-transition-matrix/756-pyramid1-grid.jpg","originalUrl":"../../../images/756-pyramid1-grid.jpg","sha256":"899cb51d7128c72a028d314c28399f7e74a77cdb933a1fb9589266109ff90fd3"},{"assetIndex":1,"bytes":30272,"contentType":"image/jpeg","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/0756-pyramid-transition-matrix/756-pyramid2-grid.jpg","originalUrl":"../../../images/756-pyramid2-grid.jpg","sha256":"cf483db23745a83e23e3873636384cd9ef0904052cafd851f3e6042ce730d0e8"}],"categories":["Hash Table","String","Backtracking","Bit Manipulation"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"You are stacking blocks to form a pyramid. Each block has a color, which is represented by a single letter. Each row of blocks contains **one less block** than the row beneath it and is centered on top.\n\nTo make the pyramid aesthetically pleasing, there are only specific **triangular patterns** that are allowed. A triangular pattern consists of a **single block** stacked on top of **two blocks**. The patterns are given as a list of three-letter strings `allowed`, where the first two characters of a pattern represent the left and right bottom blocks respectively, and the third character is the top block.\n\n- For example, `\"ABC\"` represents a triangular pattern with a `'C'` block stacked on top of an `'A'` (left) and `'B'` (right) block. Note that this is different from `\"BAC\"` where `'B'` is on the left bottom and `'A'` is on the right bottom.\n\nYou start with a bottom row of blocks `bottom`, given as a single string, that you **must** use as the base of the pyramid.\n\nGiven `bottom` and `allowed`, return `true`* if you can build the pyramid all the way to the top such that **every triangular pattern** in the pyramid is in *`allowed`*, or *`false`* otherwise*.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"alt":"Problem image","contentType":"image/jpeg","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/0756-pyramid-transition-matrix/756-pyramid1-grid.jpg","sequence":1,"sha256":"899cb51d7128c72a028d314c28399f7e74a77cdb933a1fb9589266109ff90fd3","type":"image"},{"sequence":2,"text":"Input: bottom = \"BCD\", allowed = [\"BCC\",\"CDE\",\"CEA\",\"FFF\"]\nOutput: true\nExplanation: The allowed triangular patterns are shown on the right.\nStarting from the bottom (level 3), we can build \"CE\" on level 2 and then build \"A\" on level 1.\nThere are three triangular patterns in the pyramid, which are \"BCC\", \"CDE\", and \"CEA\". All are allowed.","type":"code"},{"sequence":3,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"alt":"Problem image","contentType":"image/jpeg","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/0756-pyramid-transition-matrix/756-pyramid2-grid.jpg","sequence":4,"sha256":"cf483db23745a83e23e3873636384cd9ef0904052cafd851f3e6042ce730d0e8","type":"image"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: bottom = \"AAAA\", allowed = [\"AAB\",\"AAC\",\"BCD\",\"BBE\",\"DEF\"]\nOutput: false\nExplanation: The allowed triangular patterns are shown on the right.\nStarting from the bottom (level 4), there are multiple ways to build level 3, but trying all the possibilites, you will get always stuck before building level 1.","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `2 <= bottom.length <= 6`\n\n- `0 <= allowed.length <= 216`\n\n- `allowed[i].length == 3`\n\n- The letters in all input strings are from the set `{'A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F'}`.\n\n- All the values of `allowed` are **unique**.","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Hash Table","String","Backtracking","Bit Manipulation"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Medium","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"You are stacking blocks to form a pyramid. Each block has a color, which is represented by a single letter. Each row of blocks contains **one less block** than the row beneath it and is centered on top.\n\nTo make the pyramid aesthetically pleasing, there are only specific **triangular patterns** that are allowed. A triangular pattern consists of a **single block** stacked on top of **two blocks**. The patterns are given as a list of three-letter strings `allowed`, where the first two characters of a pattern represent the left and right bottom blocks respectively, and the third character is the top block.\n\n- For example, `\"ABC\"` represents a triangular pattern with a `'C'` block stacked on top of an `'A'` (left) and `'B'` (right) block. Note that this is different from `\"BAC\"` where `'B'` is on the left bottom and `'A'` is on the right bottom.\n\nYou start with a bottom row of blocks `bottom`, given as a single string, that you **must** use as the base of the pyramid.\n\nGiven `bottom` and `allowed`, return `true`* if you can build the pyramid all the way to the top such that **every triangular pattern** in the pyramid is in *`allowed`*, or *`false`* otherwise*.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/0756-pyramid-transition-matrix/756-pyramid1-grid.jpg]]\n\nInput: bottom = \"BCD\", allowed = [\"BCC\",\"CDE\",\"CEA\",\"FFF\"]\nOutput: true\nExplanation: The allowed triangular patterns are shown on the right.\nStarting from the bottom (level 3), we can build \"CE\" on level 2 and then build \"A\" on level 1.\nThere are three triangular patterns in the pyramid, which are \"BCC\", \"CDE\", and \"CEA\". All are allowed.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/0756-pyramid-transition-matrix/756-pyramid2-grid.jpg]]\n\nInput: bottom = \"AAAA\", allowed = [\"AAB\",\"AAC\",\"BCD\",\"BBE\",\"DEF\"]\nOutput: false\nExplanation: The allowed triangular patterns are shown on the right.\nStarting from the bottom (level 4), there are multiple ways to build level 3, but trying all the possibilites, you will get always stuck before building level 1.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `2 <= bottom.length <= 6`\n\n- `0 <= allowed.length <= 216`\n\n- `allowed[i].length == 3`\n\n- The letters in all input strings are from the set `{'A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F'}`.\n\n- All the values of `allowed` are **unique**.","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/pyramid-transition-matrix/","problemName":"Pyramid Transition Matrix","problemNumber":756,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descript